Here's the registration pattern:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    // HttpClient — one instance, reuse connections
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();

    // Data service — singleton so all ViewModels share the same cache/state
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

    // ViewModels — transient so each navigation gets fresh state
    builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
    builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

    // Pages — transient so they bind to their own ViewModel instance
    builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
    builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reuses TCP connections; avoids socket exhaustion. In production, consider `IHttpClientFactory` instead. |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | One instance shares auth tokens, cached data, and consistent state across all consumers. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation creates a fresh VM — no stale data from a previous visit. |
| Pages | **Transient** | Each page gets its own ViewModel via constructor injection, matching the transient VM lifetime. |

**Key rule of thumb:** never register a consumer with a *longer* lifetime than its dependencies (e.g., a singleton VM holding a transient service would capture a stale instance — the "captive dependency" problem). Here, singletons only depend on other singletons, and transients can depend on anything, so the graph is safe.
